The Big Picture of Statistics 202

BRFSS: Behavioral Risk Factor Surveillance System

  • is an annual telephone survey of people living the United states.
  • seeks to identify individual-level behavioral risk factors associated with premature mortality and morbidity.
    • e.g. cigarette smoking, alcohol use …
  • collected 491,773 records in 2013.
  • further info / full data available from the CDC.
  • a 20,000 record is subset available from Lab 1 of the OpenIntro Statistics course.

Definitions

  • Data: pieces of information organized into variables

    • Individuals: particular persons or objects
    • Variables: particular characteristics of individuals

  • Two Types of Variables

    • Quantitative represent numerical measurements
      • e.g. Age, Weight, and Height
    • Categorical represent categories or labels
      • e.g. Race, Gender, and Level of Education

Categorical or Quantitative?

  • Would you say that in general your health is Excellent, Very Good, Good, Fair or Poor ?
    • Categorical
  • Have you smoked at least 100 cigarettes in your entire life?
    • Categorical
  • On average, how many hours of sleep do you get in a 24-hour period?
    • Quantitative
  • What is the ZIP Code where you live?
    • Categorical

  • genhlth Would you say that in general your health is excellent, very good, good, fair, or poor?

      excellent very good good fair poor Sum
      4,657 6,972 5,675 2,019 677 20,000
    • A table of proportions:
      excellent very good good fair poor Sum
      0.23 0.35 0.28 0.10 0.03 1.00

Histogram: analog of a bar plot

Interpreting Quantitative Variables

Histogram

  1. Describe the shape
  2. Describe the center
  3. Describe the spread
  4. Note deviations from the pattern

Shapes of Quantitative Variables

Symmetric: balanced on both sides

Skewed: one tail is longer than the other

Shapes of Quantitative Variables

Unimodal: one peak

Bimodal: two peaks

Shapes of Quantitative Variables

Uniform: flat, no apparent modes

Bimodal right-skewed:

Interpreting Shape

Variables with bimodal distributions are usually mixtures of two groups.

What group might be represented by the shoulder?

  • Baby boomers

Best Actress Oscar Winners

Age at Oscar

What percent of actresses were older than 60 years?

  • Total: 7+14+8+1+2 = 32
  • Subset: 1+2 = 3
  • Answer:
    \[ \frac{3}{32} \times 100\% = 9.4\% \]

  • If n is odd, then the median is the \( \frac{n+1}{2} \) observation.

  • If n is even, then the median is the average of \( \frac{n}{2} \) and \( \frac{n}{2} + 1 \) observations

  • For these data, n=32

    • The 16th obs. is 35
    • The 17th obs. is also 35
    • the median is 35.

Median versus Mean

Consider two data sets:

Data_A 64 65 66 68 70 71 73
Data_B 64 65 66 68 70 71 730

The mean and median of Data A are:

Mean: 68.14   Median: 68

The mean and median of Data B are:

Mean: 162   Median: 68
  • The mean was pulled to the outlier.
  • The median was unchanged.

Interpreting Quantitative Variables

  1. Describe the shape
    • symmetric, right-skewed, or left-skewed
    • unimodal, bimodal, or multimodal
  2. Describe the center
    • choose mean or median
  3. Describe the spread (Friday)
  4. Note deviations from the pattern
    • possible outliers

R & RStudio

  • Intro stats often limited by small data
    • Best Actress Oscar Winners
  • Practicing statisticians use big data
    • BRFSS (½ million records) is still quite small
  • This course teaches modern data tools:
    • R is a statistical programming language.
    • RStudio is a useful interface to R.
    • We will not be programming! (later courses)
